Introduction: Metadata as Research Infrastructure

This analysis demonstrates how different types of metadata enable fundamentally different research questions in text analysis. We use the Royal Society Corpus (RSC) to show how temporal, network, topical, and authorship metadata each unlock new analytical possibilities that would be impossible without such structured information.

About the Royal Society Corpus

The Royal Society Corpus (https://fedora.clarin-d.uni-saarland.de/rsc_v6/) is a digital collection of scientific texts published by the Royal Society of London from 1665 to 1920. This corpus represents over 250 years of scientific discourse in English, making it an ideal laboratory for studying the evolution of scientific language, concepts, and communities.

An overview can be found in: Menzel, K., Knappen, J., & Teich, E. (2021). Generating linguistically relevant metadata for the Royal Society Corpus. Research in Corpus Linguistics, 9(1), 1–18. https://doi.org/10.32714/ricl.09.01.02

Knowing your data (the RSC):

  • Temporal depth: Spans the Scientific Revolution through the early 20th century
  • Institutional coherence: All texts from a single prestigious scientific institution
  • Scientific significance: Documents major discoveries and paradigm shifts in science
  • Rich metadata: Beyond just publication dates, includes author information, topics, and document types

Key corpus statistics

  • 17520 (17520) articles and papers
  • Multiple document types (articles, abstracts, reviews, proceedings)
  • Post facto topic classifications (topic modelling)
  • Author attribution and co-authorship networks
  • Standardised temporal metadata

The Central Argument: Metadata Shapes Possible Questions

The key goal from this workbook is to show how research questions are fundamentally shaped and limited by the metadata available in your dataset. Each type of metadata opens up entirely new analytical possibilities:

  • Without metadata: Only basic frequency and vocabulary analysis
  • With temporal metadata: Historical evolution, emergence patterns, diachronic change
  • With authorship metadata: Collaboration patterns, individual vs. collective discourse
  • With topical metadata: Disciplinary differences, field-specific language
  • With network metadata: Community detection, intellectual influence, social aspects of knowledge

And, of course, these lenses can be combined in various ways to conduct more and more complex analyses (although they all start from/are built on simple and understandable starting points).

N.B.: This principle applies far beyond historical corpora—whether analysing social media posts, legal documents, news articles, or any text collection. The available metadata determines what questions you can meaningfully investigate.

Data overview

Before analysis, we need to understand the structure and scope of our data. This section provides descriptive overviews of both the textual corpus and the network metadata.

Network/Community Data: Mapping Scientific Collaboration

The network data represents the social structure of Royal Society. It was created by:

  • Building a bipartite network: Authors connected to publications
  • Projecting to author-author networks: Authors linked through co-authorship
  • Community detection: Using the Louvain algorithm to identify stable relationships (1000 times per time period)
  • Temporal slicing: Creating overlapping 50-year windows with 25-year steps (slices overlap with neighbors to capture gradual transitions)

The aim of this approach is to reveal how scientists cluster into research communities, which can then be investigated on their own, or analysed and measured to see how they evolve over time.

The time slices are:

slice_1650_1699, slice_1675_1724, slice_1700_1749, slice_1725_1774, slice_1750_1799, slice_1775_1824, slice_1800_1849, slice_1825_1874, slice_1850_1899, slice_1875_1924

The network data was constructed with code/data_prep/creating_communities.r.

Corpus Overview

The Royal Society Corpus contains the full text of scientific publications along with rich metadata.

Understanding this structure is essential for designing meaningful analyses.

Metadata is saved in the corpus object, and can be accessed with docvars(rsc_corpus)$METADATA.

cat("Total documents in corpus:", ndoc(rsc_corpus), "\n")
## Total documents in corpus: 17520
cat("Corpus docvar names:", paste(names(docvars(rsc_corpus)), collapse = ", "), "\n\n")
## Corpus docvar names: doc_id, issn, title, fpage, lpage, year, volume, journal, author, type, corpusBuild, doiLink, language, jrnl, decade, period, century, pages, sentences, tokens, visualizationLink, doi, jstorLink, hasAbstract, isAbstractOf, primaryTopic, primaryTopicPercentage, secondaryTopic, secondaryTopicPercentage, authors_list, author_count, is_multi_author

The metadata saved in the corpus includes:

Document Identification & Bibliographic Info

  • doc_id: Unique identifier for each document in the corpus
  • issn: International Standard Serial Number for the journal/publication
  • title: Title of the scientific paper/article
  • fpage/lpage: First page and last page numbers where the article appears
  • year: Publication year
  • volume: Journal volume number
  • journal and jrnl: Name of the Royal Society publication, along with an abbreviated/shortened version
  • author: Author(s), seperated by a | (pipe)

Document Properties

  • type: Type of publication (article, abstract, review, proceedings, etc.)
  • language: Language of publication
  • pages: Total number of pages in the document
  • sentences: Number of sentences in the full text
  • tokens: Number of individual words/tokens in the full text

Temporal Classifications

  • decade: Which decade the document was published (1650s, 1660s, 1670s, etc.)
  • period: The 50-year period the document was published (1650, 1700, 1750, etc.)
  • century: Which century (1600, 1700, 1800, 1900)

Digital Infrastructure

  • corpusBuild: Version or build number of the corpus compilation
  • doiLink: URL link to the Digital Object Identifier
  • doi: The actual DOI string
  • visualisationLink: Link to any digital visualisations of the document
  • jstorLink: Link to JSTOR database entry (if available)

Content Structure

  • hasAbstract: Boolean indicating whether the document has an abstract
  • isAbstractOf: If this document IS an abstract, what it’s an abstract of

Topic Classifications

  • primaryTopic: Main subject classification (computationally assigned)
  • primaryTopicPercentage: Confidence/percentage/theta/θ for primary topic assignment
  • secondaryTopic: Secondary subject classification
  • secondaryTopicPercentage: Confidence/percentage/theta/θ for secondary topic

Authorship Analysis

  • authors_list: Complete list of all authors (saved as a list)
  • author_count: Number of authors on the paper
  • is_multi_author: Boolean flag for whether it has multiple authors

Understanding the Subsetting Functions

The power of metadata-driven analysis lies in our ability to create focused subsets for comparison. The helper functions in this workshop allow flexible filtering by any combination of metadata dimensions.

How the Subsetting Works

The subset_corpus() function acts as a master controller that can filter by:

  • Temporal criteria: Specific years, decades, or date ranges
  • Document types: Articles, abstracts, proceedings, etc.
  • Topics: Primary or secondary subject classifications
  • Authorship patterns: Single vs. multi-author works
  • Network communities: Authors from specific intellectual communities
  • Individual authors: Works by named scientists

This flexibility enables complex, multi-dimensional comparisons that would be impossible with text alone.

Test Individual Subsetting Functions

Analysing Text

For this portion of the workbook we will use the Quantitative Text Analysis(QTA)/Natural Language Processing(NLP) library Quanteda.

Quanteda (and many/most NLP packages) work with objects called Document Feature Matrices (or Document Term Matrices). These are, essentially, very large spreadsheets where every row represents a document and every column is a word (of all the words) in all of the documents. A toy example:

# Create a corpus - just like the RSC - of three simple sentences
test_corpus <- corpus(c("I like cats", "Cats are nice", "I am happy"))

# Create document feature matrix of our corpus
test_dfm <- tokens(test_corpus) %>%
  dfm()

# And let's look at it
print(test_dfm)
## Document-feature matrix of: 3 documents, 7 features (57.14% sparse) and 0 docvars.
##        features
## docs    i like cats are nice am happy
##   text1 1    1    1   0    0  0     0
##   text2 0    0    1   1    1  0     0
##   text3 1    0    0   0    0  1     1

It is the frequency and relationship of these features (tokens, words) that is central to NLP. We will, therefore, be analysing DFMs which are quantitative representation of our documents - figuratively “bags of words.” N.B. This also means that the human-readable text is no longer there. If you want to read a document you will need to go back to the corpus object.

For example, it becomes easy (and computationally less difficult) to identify the most frequent words (or other features):

topfeatures(test_dfm)
##     i  cats  like   are  nice    am happy 
##     2     2     1     1     1     1     1

It is, therefore, a DFM of the RSC that we will analyse going forward. However, to do this we first need to construct it.

N.B.: this can take a few minutes, depending on computational resources. An already constructed DFM can be loaded by commenting out code:

# rsc_dfm <- readRDS("../data/rsc_dfm.RDS")

start_time <- Sys.time()

# Tokenise corpus, while removing punctuation, numbers, symbols, and stopwords as well as lowercasing everything
rsc_tokens <- tokens(rsc_corpus, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE,
                      remove_symbols = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_tolower() %>%
  tokens_remove(stopwords("english"))

# Document-feature matrix
rsc_dfm <- dfm(rsc_tokens)

end_time <- Sys.time()
cat("Total time taken to tokenise and create DFM:")
## Total time taken to tokenise and create DFM:
print(end_time-start_time)
## Time difference of 1.316766 mins
#saveRDS(rsc_dfm, file = "../data/rsc_dfm.RDS")

1. Baseline: Text Without Metadata Context

The question we can ask: What are the most common concepts and patterns discussed by the Royal Society overall?

What this may reveal: Basic vocabulary, general themes, and surface-level patterns in scientific discourse across the entire corpus (multi-topic) and time period (multi-century).

Critical limitation: Without metadata, we have little context for interpretation. We can see what scientists and researchers wrote about, but not when, who wrote it, why certain terms appear together, or how usage patterns changed over time.

This baseline represents the starting point for any text analysis – but also demonstrates why metadata is essential for meaningful interpretation.

N.B.: This is a moderately large dataset. Creating and analying the text computationally can take a bit of time. It’s not at the point where high performance computing is necessary, but it may take a few minutes on a laptop.

# Compare 1700s vs 1800s using keyness analysis
# This is statistically rigorous and much simpler than manual frequency ratios

# Combine the DFMs and add period labels
combined_dfm <- rbind(dfm_1700s, dfm_1800s)
docvars(combined_dfm, "period") <- c(rep("1700s", ndoc(dfm_1700s)),
                                     rep("1800s", ndoc(dfm_1800s)))

# Calculate keyness (target = TRUE means 1800s vs 1700s)
keyness_results <- textstat_keyness(combined_dfm, 
                                    target = docvars(combined_dfm, "period") == "1800s")

# Terms that became much more prominent in 1800s

Interpreting Temporal Results

The most intuitive measurements here are n_target and n_reference. This is how many more times the word (feature) appears in one subset than the other. In this case, temperature occurs almost 30x more frequently (38399/1291). That is a strong effect size.

Additionally, chi2 is a statistical measurement the greater it is, the stronger the association between the things you’re looking at. In this case temperature with a chi2 of > 5000 is an extremely strong association. In other words, it would be unlikely for temperature to have been in one subset that many times more often than the other by chance. The p value reports whether the chi2 is statistically significant.

When exploring the features:

Look for:

  • Emerging terminology: E.g., new scientific concepts that appeared in the 1800s
  • Declining usage: How certain 18th-century terms that became less common
  • Persistent concepts: Terms that remained important across both periods

This analysis can reveal scientific developments like the emergence of electromagnetic theory, advances in chemistry, or new measurement techniques.

Quite useful! So here’s another example:

3. Topical Metadata: Disciplinary Language

Research Questions:

  • How do different scientific fields use language distinctively?
  • What terminology is field-specific vs. shared across disciplines?
  • How do interdisciplinary boundaries manifest in language use?
  • Which fields are more specialised vs. more accessible in their terminology?

Disciplinary Context: The Royal Society period (1665-1920) predates modern academic departments, so these topic classifications reflect how language may reflect undefined disciplinary boundaries. This could provide insight into the historical organisation and/or emergence of scientific knowledge before the professionalisation and specialisation that characterises modern science.

4. Combining Metadata

When multiple perspectives are brought together one can ask more complex questions. For example:

Research Questions:

  • How do multiple metadata dimensions interact to shape scientific discourse?
  • What happens when we layer temporal, topical, and social factors together?
  • How can we trace the evolution of specific scientific communities or disciplines?
  • What complex patterns emerge only when combining different types of context?

Methodological Strength(s): This represents the full potential of metadata-driven analysis—the ability to ask complex, multi-faceted questions that would be impossible with any single dimension of context.

Example Applications:

  • Tracking how specific scientific communities evolved their language over time
  • Comparing how different fields adopted new terminology during the same period
  • Analysing how collaboration patterns vary across disciplines and historical periods
  • Investigating how major scientific discoveries propagated through different networks

5. Text as variable

In the previous sections, we used metadata to subset text and compare different groups. Now we flip the approach: we use text patterns to investigate the metadata itself. This represents a fundamental shift in analytical perspective—instead of asking “How do different groups use language?”, we ask “What can language patterns tell us about historical, social, or institutional phenomena?”

Research Questions Enabled:

When did specific scientific concepts or terms first emerge and spread? Which authors were most central to developing particular fields or ideas? How can we trace the diffusion of ideas through scientific communities? What can linguistic patterns reveal about the social organisation of science?

Methodological Insight: Text becomes a lens for understanding broader patterns in scientific history, authorship, and knowledge production. We treat word usage, terminology evolution, and linguistic patterns as evidence for historical processes.

5.1 Temporal Emergence: When Did Scientific Concepts Appear?

Rather than comparing predefined time periods, we can trace when specific terms entered scientific discourse and how their usage evolved.

# Visualise concept emergence
library(ggplot2)

plot_concept_emergence <- function(usage_data, term_name) {
  ggplot(usage_data, aes(x = time_period)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = usage_rate), color = "blue", size = 1) +
    geom_point(aes(y = usage_rate), color = "blue", size = 2) +
    geom_line(aes(y = document_penetration * 100), color = "red", size = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
    geom_point(aes(y = document_penetration * 100), color = "red", size = 2) +
    scale_y_continuous(
      name = "Usage Rate (per 1000 words)",
      sec.axis = sec_axis(~./100, name = "Document Penetration (%)")
    ) +
    labs(
      title = paste("Emergence and Spread of '", term_name, "'", sep = ""),
      subtitle = "Blue = usage intensity, Red = breadth of adoption",
      x = "Decade"
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
}

plot_concept_emergence(electricity_usage, "electricity")

plot_concept_emergence(temperature_usage, "temperature")

plot_concept_emergence(evolution_usage, "evolution")

Interpreting Emergence Patterns

  • Usage Rate: How intensively is a term used when it appears (occurrences per 1000 words)
  • Document Penetration: How widely distributed is the term across different papers

Things one can look for:

  • Sudden emergence: Terms that appear rarely then spike dramatically
  • Gradual adoption: Concepts that slowly gain acceptance over decades
  • Early vs. late adoption: Whether terms start in specialist contexts then spread
  • Peak and decline: Whether certain concepts become less central over time

# Visualise cross-topic diffusion
plot_topic_diffusion <- function(diffusion_data, term_name, top_n = 8) {
  diffusion_data %>%
    filter(total_usage > 0) %>%
    slice_head(n = top_n) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = reorder(group, usage_rate), y = usage_rate)) +
    geom_col(fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(
      title = paste("Usage of '", term_name, "' Across Topics", sep = ""),
      subtitle = "Rate per 1000 words in each topic area",
      x = "Primary Topic",
      y = "Usage Rate (per 1000 words)"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()
}

plot_topic_diffusion(electricity_by_topic, "electricity")

plot_topic_diffusion(temperature_by_topic, "temperature")

Text as Evidence for Broader Phenomena

This approach demonstrates how textual patterns can serve as evidence for historical, social, and intellectual processes. Rather than treating text as the object of study, we use it as a lens for understanding the metadata itself.

We can use this to generate empirically-grounded hypotheses about historical processes that can then be investigated using traditional historical methods—creating a productive dialogue between computational and humanistic approaches to understanding the past.

6. Network/Community Metadata: Intellectual Communities

Research Questions:

  • How do different scholarly communities use language differently?
  • What concepts are community-specific vs. shared across scientific networks?
  • How do intellectual networks influence the spread of terminology?
  • Which communities serve as bridges between different scientific domains?

Methodological Strenght(s): Network metadata reveals the social structure underlying scientific knowledge production. Different communities of scientists may develop distinct vocabularies, research methods, or ways of describing phenomena—even when studying related topics.

Interpreting Community Results

Keyness reveals:

  • Community-specific vocabularies: Terms that strongly characterise each intellectual network
  • Disciplinary boundaries: How different scientific domains maintain distinct languages
  • Methodological differences: Communities may prefer different research approaches or instruments
  • Theoretical orientations: Distinct ways of conceptualising similar phenomena

These differences reflect how scientific communities develop their own research traditions, methodological preferences, and ways of understanding the natural world.

Summary

What we’ve tried to demonstrate here is that metadata can fundamentally determines what research questions are possible to ask and answer when using text. Each type of metadata creates new analytical possibilities (or lenses).

Implications for Text Analysis

  • 1. Research Design: Always begin by cataloging available metadata and considering what questions each dimension enables
  • 2. Data Collection: Invest heavily in metadata acquisition as it’s potentially more valuable than additional raw text
  • 3. Analytical Strategy: Design analysis plans that start with basic questions and allow for the addition of dimensions progressively
  • 4. Interpretation: Context from metadata is essential for moving from pattern detection to meaningful explanation
  • 5. Reproducibility: Document metadata schemas and subsetting criteria as carefully as analytical procedures

Practical Implications and strategies for your research

Two general approaches

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

  • Start simple: basic frequency analysis
  • Build Complexity by layering different metadata dimensions
  • Ask bigger questions (maybe… research questions) as you develop an understanding of your data and the substantive context

Start with your research question(s)

  • Guided by domain expertise
  • What do you want to know?
  • What metadata would enable that analysis?
  • Work backwards from question to data requirements

Concluding notes

Metadata is not optional

  • Determines analytical possibilities
  • Invest time in understanding (and enriching) metadata

Layer your analysis

  • Begin with simple, single-dimensional analyses
  • Gradually combine metadata types for richer insights
  • Each combination unlocks new research possibilities

Document structure can be metadata

Even without explicit categories, text structure provides context, e.g.:

  • Network analysis from co-occurrence patterns
  • Temporal patterns from publication sequences
  • Topic modeling to categorise document
  • Text itself (tokens) can be used to understand metadata
